  "text": "the effective two-mode nonlinearity χ in H nl (8) is very small when the condensates a and b overlap spatially. This gives the possibility to tune the non-linearity [CITATION_1] by either controlling the spatial overlap between the two species as done [CITATION_2] or by using a Feshbach resonance changing the inter-species coupling constant g ab as done in [CITATION_3] . A fundamental source of decoherence in these experiments is two-body losses in the state F = 2. A theoretical analysis [CITATION_4] shows that in typical experimental conditions these losses limit the squeezing to about ξ 2 min ≃ 6 × 10 −2 . For cold samples this limit is above the limit imposed by non-zero temperature. In the case of [CITATION_5] we could explain in detail the squeezing results using a zero-temperature model including spatial dynamics and including particle losses and technical noise (dephasing noise) as sources of decoherence, the latter being dominant [CITATION_6] 18] .",
